<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,151,536]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,404,429]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin adjective, “ 
<emphasis box="[646,713,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">brevis</emphasis>
”, meaning short, and the adjective “ 
<emphasis box="[1126,1205,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">pilosus</emphasis>
”, covered with hair, in reference to the conspicuous eye hairs that appear to be slightly shorter than those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1213,1344,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Houghia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurifera">
<emphasis box="[1213,1344,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H. aurifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Houghia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipilosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H. longipilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, described below.
</paragraph>
